latestIgtvVideos.caption:
With @varundvn discussing 'Violence against Doctors' - June 5th, 2021.

Happy to share that this session with Varun has been published in over 90 news articles across the country (including Times of India, Indian Express, Hindustan Times, Republic, Aaj Tak, Hindi news 18, The Evening Standard, The Free Press Journal, Bharat Times, Dainik Bhaskar, Filmfare, and many more). This also includes publications in over 8 languages and from over 19 states.

It has also been published on the front page of newspapers, including Bombay Times, Delhi Times, Pune Times, Bangalore Times, Calcutta Times, Hyderabad Times, Chennai Times, and some others. I am grateful that this has now reached millions of Indians across the country and hopefully created some awareness regarding this very serious issue.

However, I do not feel it is an achievement or a milestone of any sort. The very fact that a discussion of this sort needs to take place, is in itself a matter of worry.

Today, we've raised our voice. Today, we've been heard. Today, we're being talked about. Today, we can at least smile.

This is just one step in the right direction. This is just the beginning.

A doctor’s take on few things to keep in mind before you pick up that protein bar.

PUNE BOOK FESTIVAL 2024 ✨

Still pinching myself after an incredible experience at the Pune Book Festival! Walking into a packed venue as a debut author was a moment I’ll never forget. The moderated session was full of thoughtful questions and conversations that reminded me why I wrote this book in the first place.

Meeting so many wonderful people—especially those who’ve followed and supported my journey on Instagram—was the absolute highlight of the day.

Signing copies of my book, hearing your thoughts, and seeing your excitement made it all so real. It’s amazing to see curiosity and the love for science come alive in a room filled with such energy and enthusiasm. 

This journey has been so rewarding, and I couldn’t have asked for a better way to share it than with all of you in Pune.

Here’s to breaking myths, spreading knowledge, and staying curious, together! Thank you, Pune, for all the love. ❤️

#PuneBookFestival #DebutAuthor #ButWhatDoesScienceSay

Share it with your friends and family and let them know about this hidden fat!

In a world driven by convenience, it’s easy to reach for medication for every little discomfort. 

The healthcare industry thrives on our dependency, and Big Pharma’s growth is fueled by our habits. With India’s pharmaceutical market booming at $13.16 billion, it’s worth questioning : all our health expenses are truly necessary?

As a doctor, I advocate for prevention over cure. The human body has an incredible capacity to heal and adapt when given the right environment.

By choosing holistic health solutions, 
improving your eating habits, and prioritizing long-term well-being over quick fixes, you can often avoid the need for unnecessary pills.

Think about it, and let me know in the comments below: how often do you pop a pill?
